238. -1721. A very large shield from fort St. George in the East Indies by Mr Governr. Yale. made of an Elephant or rhinoc eros hide. 226. -1722. A fan or umbrella made of the leaf of the 148 Lantor. ✓ 13 -1723. A knife wt. a scabbard & haft made of the bone of wt. a loop in the scabbard to hang by the girdle. 25 A.W.F. 199. -1724. Artificiall butterflies made of silk the wings
painted & antennae pearl sett on wire with.
a flower in the midle from Mr. Muhleman.
-1725. Tobacco rolled up to be smoakd wt. out the
help of a pipe. Dr. Massy.
-1726. A triangle cutt in Chrystall glasse said to be used as
a shew stone or conjuring instrument.
O. 245. -1727. A candle & piece of soap made of the myrtle
wax berries. from New England by Mr. Wynthorp.
O. 245. -1728. An Indian breast plate which they wear when they go to
28 b? warr or at any great feast, made of shells out of the up
Country freshwater lakes, with the collar consisting of the
blue ones
& white shells where of four make a penny & six white
ones, they drill the holes with the point of a sharp flint
& work them round on a fine gritty stone Id.
O. 245. -1729. An Indian spoon & bowl , made of the knot of a tree which they
burn hollow & then smooth & polish wt. a sharp flint & then
soak it in their minerall springs to dye it. Out of this they
eat their suckatash, which is venison, fish & Indian corn
boild together. Id.
O. 245. -1730. An Indian spoon made of the breast bone of a An Indian spoon made of the breast bone of a pinguin made anno
1702. made by Papenau an Indian whose squaw had both her leggs gan=
=grened & rotted off to her knees & was cured by bathing in balsam water
made by Winthrop Esqr. N. England. The method was thus, He ordered two ox
bladders to be filled wt. his rare balsamic liquor made warm & the
stumps putt into the bladders & tyed above the knees the bladders wt. the
water was kept constantly blood warm & the leggs were perfectly
cured in a few days time. Id.
